  "prompt": "What is social stratification? What are some examples?",
  "response": "Social stratification is a system of social hierarchy in which individuals and groups are ranked in a hierarchical manner based on various criteria such as wealth, power, prestige, race, education, or occupation. This hierarchical arrangement creates unequal access to resources, opportunities, and social mobility.\n\nExamples of social stratification include:\n\n1. Economic/Class Stratification\n- Upper class (wealthy)\n- Middle class\n- Working class\n- Lower/working poor\n- Impoverished class\n\n2. Caste System\n- Historical example in India\n- Strict hereditary social hierarchy\n- Limited social mobility\n- Predetermined social status based on birth\n\n3. Racial Stratification\n- Systemic inequalities based on racial identity\n- Unequal access to education, employment, and resources\n- Historical examples like segregation in the United States\n\n4. Gender Stratification\n- Unequal opportunities and treatment based on gender\n- Wage gaps\n- Limited leadership positions for women\n- Differential social expectations\n\n5. Educational Stratification\n- Differences in educational opportunities\n- Unequal access to quality education\n- Impact on future socioeconomic prospects\n\n6. Occupational Stratification\n- Different social status associated with different professions\n- Varying levels of income and prestige\n- Hierarchical ranking of jobs\n\nThese systems of stratification create persistent social inequalities and impact individuals' life chances and opportunities.",
